 about classic subversive texts (such as Nabokov's Lolita), performances (Pussy Riot), and recent, but also subversive, films. Other articles discuss such authors as Vladimir Sorokin, such sociocultural discourses as the discourse of scientific intelligentsia; post-Soviet adaptations of Socialist Realism, and contemporary trends of "complex" literature, as well as literary characters turned into cultural tropes (the Strugatsky's progressors). The book will be interesting for teachers and scholars of contemporary Russian literature and culture; it can be used both in undergraduate and graduate courses.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMotion pictureszRussia (Federation)xHistory and criticism. 0aPostmodernism (Literature)zRussia (Federation) 0aPostmodernism (Literature)zRussia (Federation). 0aPostmodernismzRussia (Federation) 0aPostmodernismzRussia (Federation). 0aRussian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRussian literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aLoznitsa, Sergei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTodorovsky, Valery, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVeledinsky, Aleksandr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781618115591zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781618115591zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781618115591.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  a